      <!-- About Section -->
      <section id="about" class="container content-section text-center">
          <div class="row">
              <div class="col-lg-8 col-lg-offset-2">
                  <h2>About Us</h2>
                  <p>A common misconception about the Ironman is that prior to race week you required to work harder, to then completely shut down and rest.
                    Studies proved it is more advantageous to gradually decrease work-rate. </p>
                  <p>The program starts with three to four days of aerobic recovery sessions and days off, followed by shorter training sessions at threshold, and shorter aerobic base work the weekend before your Ironman.</p>
                  <p>The week of Ironman follows a similar pattern, with further reduced sessions. You should gradually feel more rested, while staying sharp. </p>
                  <p>Stay mentally engaged with your training, and avoid feeling like you are hanging on for the taper. Once you start racing, the weeks of training click in, the cobwebs shake off and your fitness will shine through!</p>
              </div>
          </div>
      </section>
      <!-- Training Section -->
      <section id="training" class="container content-section text-center">
          <div class="row">
              <div class="col-lg-8 col-lg-offset-2">
                <h2>Training Structure</h2>
                  <p>This training program was created to prepare for an ironman in the final months, therefore the structure is central.
                  The week’s structure is rather routine in which disciplines will be exercised. Mondays are always kept for swimming, and occasional sessions on Thursdays. </p>
                  <p>Running and Cycling are more often than not done together and in succession, on Tuesdays, Thursdays and Saturdays.
                  It is important to follow the order which was shown on the exercise to prepare yourself for a certain challenges you may face during the transitions.
                  The other days are free rest days, which are mandatory because an injury 2 months prior to race day can kill all your chances to properly compete.</p>
              </div>
          </div>
      </section>
